<methodology slug="gitops-secrets-security">
  <metadata>
    <tier>pro</tier>
    <group>infra</group>
    <domain>cicd-engineer</domain>
    <summary>Secret management and security hardening for GitOps: SOPS with age/KMS, Sealed Secrets, External Secrets Operator, RBAC least-privilege, and AI-agent-specific security gotchas.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>gitops</tag>
      <tag>secrets</tag>
      <tag>sops</tag>
      <tag>security</tag>
      <tag>kubernetes</tag>
    </tags>
    <category>gitops</category>
    <difficulty>advanced</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-27</created>
    <related>
      <ref slug="gitops-core-principles"/>
      <ref slug="gitops-repository-structure"/>
      <ref slug="secrets-management"/>
    </related>
  </metadata>

  <content>
    <title>GitOps Secret Management and Security</title>

    <summary>Secrets in GitOps require explicit tooling because plaintext secrets in Git are a critical vulnerability. Three mature solutions exist: SOPS (encrypt-in-place, Git-native), Sealed Secrets (cluster-encrypted CRDs), and External Secrets Operator (pull from Vault/AWS SM/GCP SM). Each has distinct trust models. Security hardening covers RBAC, network policies, and AI-agent-specific risks.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>The GitOps pull model means the cluster operator reads from Git directly — any plaintext secret committed to the config repo is exposed to everyone with repo read access, CI logs, and any historical access. All three secret solutions solve this differently: SOPS encrypts the YAML value in-place (secret stays in Git, encrypted); Sealed Secrets uses asymmetric encryption tied to a specific cluster key (secret stays in Git, sealed); ESO references secrets stored in external vaults (no secret data ever in Git).</p>
      <p>AI agents working on GitOps repos create additional secret exposure risks: they may summarize secret values in PR descriptions, commit decrypted files by accident, or leak credentials through helm values output.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Any GitOps setup — secret management is mandatory, not optional.</item>
        <item>SOPS: when the team controls key management (age keys, AWS KMS, GCP KMS) and wants secrets to live in Git in encrypted form.</item>
        <item>Sealed Secrets: when secrets should be cluster-scoped and you want a simple CLI (kubeseal) without external KMS dependency.</item>
        <item>External Secrets Operator: when secrets already live in Vault, AWS Secrets Manager, GCP Secret Manager, or Azure Key Vault and you want to avoid duplicating them.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Sealed Secrets: do not use across multiple clusters without managing cluster-specific keys — a sealed secret from cluster A cannot be decrypted by cluster B.</item>
        <item>SOPS with shared age keys: avoid single shared key for all environments — use per-environment keys so staging keys cannot decrypt prod secrets.</item>
        <item>External Secrets without network policy: ESO requires egress from the cluster to the secret store — ensure network policies allow this only from the ESO namespace.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="sops">
      <p>SOPS (Secrets OPerationS) encrypts YAML/JSON values in-place. The file stays in Git; individual values are encrypted with AES256-GCM using a key from age, AWS KMS, GCP KMS, or Azure Key Vault. Flux natively supports SOPS decryption via the kustomize-controller.</p>
      <example type="good" title="SOPS-encrypted Kubernetes Secret in Git">
        <code lang="yaml"><![CDATA[
# secrets/production/db-secret.yaml — committed to Git encrypted
apiVersion: v1
kind: Secret
metadata:
  name: db-credentials
type: Opaque
data:
  username: ENC[AES256_GCM,data:abc123==,iv:xyz==,tag:def==]
  password: ENC[AES256_GCM,data:ghi456==,iv:uvw==,tag:jkl==]
sops:
  kms:
    - arn: arn:aws:kms:us-east-1:123456789:key/abc-def-ghi
  lastmodified: '2025-01-15T10:00:00Z'
  mac: ENC[AES256_GCM,data:mac==,iv:maciv==,tag:mactag==]
  version: 3.7.3
]]></code>
        <note>Only the values are encrypted; keys and structure are visible. sops.kms records which KMS key was used for auditing.</note>
      </example>
      <example type="good" title="Flux SOPS decryption configuration">
        <code lang="yaml"><![CDATA[
# clusters/production/flux-system/kustomization.yaml
apiVersion: kustomize.toolkit.fluxcd.io/v1
kind: Kustomization
metadata:
  name: secrets
  namespace: flux-system
spec:
  interval: 10m
  sourceRef:
    kind: GitRepository
    name: gitops-repo
  path: ./secrets/production
  prune: true
  decryption:
    provider: sops
    secretRef:
      name: sops-age  # Kubernetes secret holding the age private key
]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="external-secrets">
      <p>External Secrets Operator (ESO) creates Kubernetes Secrets by pulling values from external stores at reconcile time. No secret data ever lives in Git.</p>
      <example type="good" title="ExternalSecret pulling from AWS Secrets Manager">
        <code lang="yaml"><![CDATA[
apiVersion: external-secrets.io/v1beta1
kind: ExternalSecret
metadata:
  name: db-credentials
  namespace: my-app
spec:
  refreshInterval: 1h
  secretStoreRef:
    kind: ClusterSecretStore
    name: aws-secrets-manager
  target:
    name: db-credentials
    creationPolicy: Owner
  data:
    - secretKey: username
      remoteRef:
        key: prod/my-app/db
        property: username
    - secretKey: password
      remoteRef:
        key: prod/my-app/db
        property: password
]]></code>
        <note>refreshInterval controls how often ESO polls the external store. ClusterSecretStore is shared cluster-wide; SecretStore is namespace-scoped.</note>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="rbac-security">
      <rules>
        <rule>
          <statement>Apply RBAC least-privilege to the GitOps operator's service account: it needs only the permissions to apply resources in target namespaces, not cluster-admin.</statement>
          <rationale>A compromised GitOps operator with cluster-admin can apply arbitrary resources including ClusterRoleBindings — least-privilege limits blast radius to namespaces the operator manages.</rationale>
        </rule>
        <rule>
          <statement>Configure network policies to restrict egress from GitOps operator pods to only: the Git provider (443), the container registry, and any secret stores (Vault, AWS SM endpoint).</statement>
          <rationale>Without network policy, a compromised operator can exfiltrate secrets to arbitrary endpoints; restricting egress to known destinations contains the impact.</rationale>
        </rule>
        <rule>
          <statement>Enable audit logging on the Kubernetes API server and configure alerts for: ClusterRoleBinding creation, Secret reads outside expected namespaces, and wildcard RBAC rules.</statement>
          <rationale>GitOps changes are audited at the Git level, but direct kubectl or API calls bypass Git — audit logs catch out-of-band changes that indicate compromise or drift.</rationale>
        </rule>
        <rule>
          <statement>Require human approval for any PR that modifies RBAC resources (ClusterRole, ClusterRoleBinding, Role, RoleBinding) — enforce via CODEOWNERS or branch protection requiring a security reviewer.</statement>
          <rationale>RBAC widening is a privilege escalation vector; automated approvals or single-reviewer merges leave no second set of eyes on the most sensitive change type.</rationale>
        </rule>
      </rules>
    </section>

    <section name="agent-security-gotchas">
      <p>AI-agent-specific security risks in GitOps workflows:</p>
      <list>
        <item>Secret leakage via PR description: agents may include decrypted values in PR body when explaining changes — instruct agents to never include secret values in commit messages or PR descriptions.</item>
        <item>Accidental SOPS decryption: never run sops --decrypt in an agent's working directory and then let it git add .; always use git diff --staged to inspect before commit.</item>
        <item>kubectl get secret -o yaml dump: agents debugging cluster state may emit plaintext base64-encoded secrets to logs or terminal output — route secret inspection through a password-scrubber-agent.</item>
        <item>Helm values rendering: helm template --debug prints all values including secrets passed as --set; capture output and scrub before logging.</item>
        <item>Auto-merge bots + ArgoCD auto-sync: an agent that auto-merges its own PRs combined with ArgoCD auto-sync creates zero-human-approval deployments to production — require at minimum one human review at the production boundary.</item>
        <item>Cross-environment contamination: agents with access to both staging and prod config repos may accidentally commit a staging secret or image to the prod overlay.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="security-prompts">
      <prompt purpose="secrets-management-design"><![CDATA[
Design a secrets management strategy for GitOps.

Requirements:
- Secret types: [database creds / API keys / certificates]
- Compliance requirements: [list]
- Cloud provider: [AWS / GCP / Azure / on-prem]
- Rotation requirements: [automatic / manual, frequency]

Recommend:
1. Secret management solution (SOPS / Sealed Secrets / External Secrets)
2. Integration with GitOps workflow
3. Key management strategy
4. Rotation procedure
5. Audit logging setup
]]></prompt>
      <prompt purpose="gitops-security-audit"><![CDATA[
Perform a security audit of my GitOps setup.

Current configuration:
- GitOps tool: [ArgoCD / Flux]
- Repository access: [describe]
- RBAC: [describe]
- Network policies: [yes / no]
- Secrets management: [describe]

Analyze:
1. Attack surface assessment
2. Credential exposure risks
3. RBAC gaps
4. Network security issues
5. Recommended remediations prioritized by severity
]]></prompt>
    </section>

    <section name="safe-sync-helper">
      <p>Drift-aware ArgoCD sync helper script that refuses dangerous changes:</p>
      <example type="good" title="argocd-safe-sync.sh — diff first, refuse on dangerous changes">
        <code lang="bash"><![CDATA[
#!/usr/bin/env bash
# argocd-safe-sync.sh — diff first, refuse on dangerous changes
set -euo pipefail
APP=${1:?app name}
DIFF=$(argocd app diff "$APP" --output json || true)
if echo "$DIFF" | jq -e '.[] | select(.kind=="Deployment") | .target.spec.replicas < .live.spec.replicas' >/dev/null; then
  echo "REFUSE: replica decrease detected"; exit 2
fi
if echo "$DIFF" | jq -e '.[] | select(.kind=="ClusterRoleBinding")' >/dev/null; then
  echo "REFUSE: RBAC change requires human approval"; exit 2
fi
argocd app sync "$APP" --prune --timeout 300
argocd app wait "$APP" --health --timeout 600
]]></code>
        <note>Run this instead of bare argocd app sync in automated pipelines. Extend the jq selectors for your specific dangerous-change set.</note>
      </example>
    </section>

    <checklist>
      <check>No plaintext secrets in Git — either SOPS-encrypted, Sealed, or ESO-referenced.</check>
      <check>Secret management solution deployed and tested (SOPS age key / Sealed Secrets controller / ESO ClusterSecretStore).</check>
      <check>Per-environment keys for SOPS — staging key cannot decrypt prod secrets.</check>
      <check>GitOps operator RBAC scoped to target namespaces only, no cluster-admin.</check>
      <check>Network policies restrict operator egress to Git provider + registry + secret stores.</check>
      <check>Audit logging enabled on API server; alerts for ClusterRoleBinding creation and wildcard RBAC.</check>
      <check>CODEOWNERS requiring security reviewer for RBAC resource changes.</check>
      <check>Agent workflows audited: no kubectl get secret -o yaml in CI logs; no helm template --debug output in PR bodies.</check>
      <check>Backup of age private key or KMS key ARN stored separately from the cluster.</check>
      <check>Secret rotation schedule documented and tested.</check>
    </checklist>

